{{wiktionary}} [[File:Krypton discharge tube.jpg|thumb|A [[discharge tube]] filled with Krypton]] '''Krypton''' is a [[noble gas]] which means it does not react with many other elements. It is clear and has no taste or smell.<ref name=ad>{{cite web |url= http://www.credoreference.com/entry/apdst/krypton |title=Krypton |first= |last= |work=Academic Press Dictionary of Science and Technology |year=2006 |accessdate=17 June 2011}}</ref> The atmosphere is only about one millionth part krypton.<ref name=ad/> The name ''kypton'' comes from the [[Greek language|Greek]] word ''kryptos'' meaning hidden. It is used in [[fluorescent lamp]]s, flashbulbs, and as a [[wavelength]] standard. The [[metre]] is defined as 1,650,763.73 wavelengths in a vacuum of krypton gas.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.webelements.com/krypton/ |title=WebElements Periodic Table of the Elements |first= |last= |work=webelements.com |year=2011 [last update] |accessdate=17 June 2011}}</ref> Krypton has very few [[compound]]s.
==Uses== The main use for krypton is to make light. There is one main type of krypton light bulbs. This is called a [[gas discharge lamp]]. There are three main types of these. First is a low energy gas discharge lamp or "neon light". Low energy gas discharge lights made from krypton are near white to green. Second is a high energy short length of time gas discharge light or "flash bulb". These are mostly used for [[photography]]. They are bright blue-white. Third is a high energy gas discharge light. This third kind is mostly used to light airport runways. They are also bright blue-white.
Krypton is number 36 on the [[periodic table]]. Its symbol is Kr.
==History== Krypton was found by Sir [[William Ramsay]] and [[Morris Travers]] in Great Britain in 1898.<ref>{{cite book |title=A text-book of inorganic chemistry, Volume 1 |last=Friend |first=John Newton |year=1914 |publisher=Griffin & Company |page=346 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=hgtDAAAAIAAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=17 June 2011}}</ref> Ramsay was given the 1904 [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] for his work on noble gases.<ref>{{cite book |title=Nobel laureates in chemistry, 1901–1992 |last=James |first=Laylin K. |year=1993 |publisher=[[Chemical Heritage Foundation]] |isbn=0841226903 |page=23 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=jEy67gEvIuMC&source=gbs_navlinks_s |accessdate=17 June 2011}}</ref> It was a difficult gas to discover; Ramsay suspected it existed but only found it by removing other gases.<ref name=kd>{{cite web |url= http://www.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/2008/05/dayintech_0530 |title=May 30, 1898: Krypton Discovered, Decades Before Superman Arrives |first=Randy |last=Alfred |work=wired.com |year=30 May, 2008 |accessdate=29 June 2011}}</ref> This is why he gave it the name Krypton.<ref name=kd/> There is no mineral called [[Kryptonite]] or [[planet]] called Krypton, which features in the [[Superman]] comics by [[Jerry Siegel]] and [[Joe Shuster]].<ref name=kd/> The fictional planet is probably better known than the real chemical element called Krypton.<ref name=kd/>
