{{wiktionary}} '''Radium''' is a [[chemical element]] with the [[atomic number]] 88 and symbol Ra on the [[periodic table]]. It was discovered by [[Marie Curie]] and [[Pierre Curie]] in the form of radium chloride in 1898. It is an almost pure-white [[alkaline earth metal]], but when it is exposed to oxygen, it turns black quickly. All [[isotope|isotopes]] of radium are radioactive, and it glows faint blue because of this.
It's used in several things, like luminous watches, which are now banned because they can cause [[radiation poisoning]]. This was caused because of a law suit that involved 5 women ( [[radium girls]] ) that suffered from many disabilities because of the prolonged exposure they had to the element [[radium]].
