'''Neptunium''' is a [[chemical]] [[Chemical element|element]] that has the symbol '''Np''' on the [[periodic table]]. It has the atomic number 93 which means it has 93 [[proton]]s and [[electron]]s in its [[atom]]s. It is named after the [[planet]] [[Neptune (planet)|Neptune]] in the same way as [[Uranium]] is named after the planet [[Uranus]]. '''Neptunium''' was discovered in the year of '''1940''' by two men named '''Edwin McMillan''' and '''Phillip H. Abelson'''. Neptunium is a silvery- metallic element and is radio-active. Its melting point is 637 degrees Celsius and it's boiling point is 4000 degrees Celsius. {{chem-stub}}
